# GitOps argocd

```
k create namespace argocd
```

Also need to bootstrap metallb

## Bootstraps

### Metallb

Need an external ip, so bootstrap metallb:

```
helm repo add metallb https://metallb.github.io/metallb
helm install metallb metallb/metallb --namespace metallb-system --set speaker.ignoreExcludeLB=true --create-namespace --version 0.15.3
kubectl apply -f gitops/apps/metallb_config.yaml
```

Nginx test:


```
kubectl create deployment test-nginx --image=nginx
kubectl expose deployment test-nginx --port=80 --type=LoadBalancer
kubectl get svc test-nginx
```

Once an external IP appears, test it:

```
curl http://<external-ip>
```

Delete:

```
kubectl delete deployment test-nginx
kubectl delete svc test-nginx
```

### Argo

Install argo:

```
helm repo add argo https://argoproj.github.io/argo-helm
helm repo update
helm install argocd argo/argo-cd -n argocd --create-namespace --version 7.8.23 --set server.service.type=LoadBalancer
```

```
kubectl apply -f gitops/apps/argocd_config.yaml
```

```
kubectl get svc argocd-server -n argocd
```

```
kubectl get svc argocd-server -n argocd
NAME            TYPE           CLUSTER-IP       EXTERNAL-IP   PORT(S)                      AGE
argocd-server   LoadBalancer   10.109.227.206   10.1.4.102    80:31410/TCP,443:32673/TCP   2m29s
```

We have an external ip we can use


```
argocd admin initial-password -n argocd
argocd login 10.1.4.102 --insecure
argocd Gccount update-password
```

Login using `admin`
W5J9wunoJw8nQYKD

And now we can login at `http://<external-ip>` via the browser too!

## Intilize GitOps

```
argocd repo add https://git.hietala.xyz/tree/home-ops.git --username admin --password 2cfbfa5cc8cb0ada21333c729d0379517ef7d1e0
```

```
argocd repo list
TYPE  NAME  REPO                                       INSECURE  OCI    LFS    CREDS  STATUS      MESSAGE  PROJECT
git         https://git.hietala.xyz/tree/home-ops.git  false     false  false  false  Successful
```

Then bootstrap the "app of apps" setup, which will load everything in `apps/`:

```
kubectl apply -f gitops/app-of-apps.yaml
```

## Automatically update versions using Renovate

Token with read/write permissions.

```
kubectl create secret generic renovate-token --namespace renovate --from-literal=RENOVATE_TOKEN=<token>
```

```
kubectl get secret renovate-token -n renovate -o jsonpath='{.data.RENOVATE_TOKEN}' | base64 -d
```

Test:

```
kubectl create job -n renovate --from=cronjob/renovate renovate-manual
```

You can also see logs with:

```
tree@winterfell ~/c/home-ops> kubectl logs -n renovate -l job-name=renovate-manual -f
```

And there's also a nice UI for this.

# New bootstrap with cilium

```
terraform apply
```

`talosctl -n 10.1.4.10 health` will stop at:

```
waiting for all k8s nodes to report ready: ...
waiting for all k8s nodes to report ready: some nodes are not ready: [talos-cp1 talos-cp2 talos-cp3]
```

Should install gateway API before installing cilium:

```
kubectl apply -f https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/gateway-api/releases/download/v1.2.1/standard-install.yaml
```

Now install cilium:

```
helm install cilium cilium/cilium \
  --namespace kube-system \
  --version 1.17.2 \
  --set kubeProxyReplacement=true \
  --set k8sServiceHost=10.1.4.100 \
  --set k8sServicePort=6443 \
  --set l2announcements.enabled=true \
  --set externalIPs.enabled=true \
  --set gatewayAPI.enabled=true \
  --set ipam.mode=kubernetes \
  --set operator.replicas=1
  --set securityContext.privileged=true
```

```
kubectl apply -f gitops/apps/cilium_config.yaml
```

Needed to work with Talos:

```yaml
securityContext:
  privileged: true
```

Can test with nginx, should work properly.

Then setup argocd as before

For the impatiant:

```
kubectl annotate applications -n argocd --all argocd.argoproj.io/refresh=hard
```

